result.execSummary:
The defendant Travis Gene Hamm was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Movable Property <=$2500, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).
  • Attempt Manuf/Deliver Amphetamine(<=3g), a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(e)1.
  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

miscConds.notes: Restitution is joint and several with co-defendant.    Restitution be paid on a schedule established by the agent.

Defendant is ordered to pay the $250.00 DNA surcharge, provide a sample for testing through the Dept. of Corrections as required in felony convictions.  Fess, surcharges and costs to be paid on a schedule established by the agent.
Defendant shall attend counseling, evaluations, treatments programming as deemed appropriate by the agent releasing all records to the agent upon request

Defendant shall not possess or consume any alcohol, and not go into places that sell alcohol except incidentally such as a grocery store, convenience store or gas station or other such place where alcohol is not sold for consumption on the premises.  Defendant is to maintain absolute sobriety.    Defendant shall not possess or consume any medication or drug except as may be specifically prescribed by a medical professional for defendant, and then shall be taken only as prescribed.  The defendant shall have no contact with Eugene Pogodzinski of any kind, whether direct or indirect, including in person, in writing, by phone, by e-mail or other electronic means, through a third party or in any other way.

The defendant shall pay Department of Correction fees as directed by the agent.  The defendant shall submit to random urine testing/PBTs as required by the agent or any law enforcement.  
Contact with Stacey Stewart is allowed unless agent has reason to rule otherwise.  If the defendant would test positive two times while submitting to a random urine test or a PBT, the contact with Stacey Stewart will be prohibited.
The defendant is to submit to an Alcohol and Other Drug Assessment (AODA) and follow the recommendations, releasing the findings to the agent.
